<section xml:id="section-graphing-equations">

    <title>Graphing Equations</title>

    <p>We have learned how to plot points in a coordinate system. Next, we will learn how to graph equations, like <m>y=-2x+5</m> and <m>y=x^2\text{.}</m> What's special about these equations is that they are in the form <m>y=\ldots</m> with only <m>x</m>-variables on the right. That makes them relatively easy to graph with a little bit of patience.</p>

    <figure>
        <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
        <video youtube="33kaIpvncag" />
    </figure>

    <p>We are trying to take an equation like <m>y=-2x+3</m> and produce a picture like <xref ref="figure-graph-line">Figure</xref>. What is this picture? The background for it is the entire Cartesian plane. But the part that matters now is all those points that have been colored in. There are so many of them that together, they form what looks like a straight line.</p>

    <sidebyside widths="31% 31% 31%"> 
        <caption>Graphs of the Equation <m>y=-2x+3</m></caption>
        <figure>
            <caption>A few points<ellipsis/></caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,5)} node[left]{$(-1,5)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,3)} node[above right]{$(0,3)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,1)} node[above right]{$(1,1)$};;
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,-1)} node[below left]{$(2,-1)$};;
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,-3)} node[below left]{$(3,-3)$};;
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4,-5)} node[above right]{$(4,-5)$};;
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <figure>
            <caption>More points<ellipsis /></caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1.5,6) (-1.2,5.4) (-1,5) (-0.8,4.6) (-0.3, 3.6) (0,3) (0.4,2.2) (1,1) (1.1,0.8) (1.7,-0.4) (2,-1) (2.3,-1.6) (2.6,-2.2) (3,-3) (3.5,-4) (4,-5) (4.3,-5.6) (4.8,-6.6)};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="figure-graph-line">
            <caption>So many points it looks like a straight line</caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[]
                            \addplot+[domain=-2:5] {-2*x+3};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>Each point has an <m>x</m>-value and a <m>y</m>-value, and our intention is that substituting these into <m>y=-2x+3</m> makes a true equation.</p>

